<section class="section section-gray">
  <div class="container">
    <p class="section-number">06, Recent repairs</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">Marvel jobs from across the territory.</h2>

    <p class="lead">Three representative service calls — model, symptom, diagnosis, repair, and cost. Names and addresses omitted; technical scenarios are typical of what we see on Marvel service.</p>

    <div class="repair-grid">
      <div class="repair-card">
        <h3>Marvel ML24WSS3RS dual-zone wine refrigerator, Beverly Hills</h3>
        <p><strong>Symptom:</strong> Wine cabinet running 7°F above setpoint — owner had set both zones to 55°F (red) and 48°F (white), unit was holding 62°F and 55°F respectively. Occasional clicking sound from the back of the unit. Issue had developed over 3 weeks. Unit was 5 years old.</p>
        <p><strong>Diagnosis:</strong> Classic 2016-2020 ML-series compressor relay failure pattern. Relay sticking intermittently — compressor running short cycles and dropping out before pulling temperatures to setpoint. Condenser coils inspected and found heavily fouled with carpet dust from the adjacent home-bar carpet. Paired-component opportunity.</p>
        <p><strong>Repair:</strong> Compressor relay replacement with OEM Marvel part (in stock on truck). Condenser coil cleaning to bare metal. Verified normal compressor cycling and temperature pull-down to setpoint over 8-hour soak. Customer also asked about HumidiCool sensor — tested clean, no replacement needed.</p>
        <p><strong>Cost & time:</strong> $325 total (relay + coil cleaning). Same-day, 90 minutes on-site.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="repair-card">
        <h3>Marvel MO24RAS1RS outdoor refrigerator, Malibu pool deck</h3>
        <p><strong>Symptom:</strong> Owner noticed unit not pulling down to setpoint reliably during summer afternoons (cabinet temp drifting 8-10°F above setpoint when ambient hit mid-90s). Worked fine through spring and fall. Unit was 7 years old, in a Malibu beachside outdoor kitchen.</p>
        <p><strong>Diagnosis:</strong> Condenser fan motor running at reduced RPM — year 7 outdoor unit, bearing wear consistent with the accelerated outdoor service curve. Also noted coastal-humidity corrosion on the door gasket lower edge (year 7 on a coastal address — within normal service window for that location). Compressor measured within spec.</p>
        <p><strong>Repair:</strong> Condenser fan motor replacement with OEM Marvel part. Door gasket replacement on the same visit (paired-component preventive service — owner agreed when we showed the corrosion). Verified normal pull-down to setpoint in mid-day summer ambient on test cycle.</p>
